        <h3>mpc related</h3>
        <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 10px">
          <li>
            <a class="toggle" id="showdiv10">
              - what is the required hardware?
            </a>
            <div id="div10" style="display: none">
              <div>
                you must have an akai mpc drum machine with a 16-pad layout that
                is compatible with the newer .pgm file format. unfortunately, i don't
                know which mpcs can load this format, but they should work on anything newer than a 1000 (such as the
                MPC Renaissance, Studio, Touch, Live, or X).
              </div>
              <div>
                as you can read
                <a href="https://www.mpc-samples.com/article/mpc-file-compatibility-1" target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">here</a>, there's more than one .pgm file format. the files
                on this site were generated using the MPC1000/2500 file format, but that doesn't necessarily mean they
                won't
                work on older MPCs.
              </div>
              <div>
                you will also need a midi sound module to be able to receive midi
                out messages from your mpc. the .pgm files DO NOT WORK WITH SAMPLE TUNING OR KEYGROUPS.
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>

          <li>
            <a class="toggle" id="showdiv2">
              - what if the files don't work on my mpc older mpc?!
            </a>
            <div id="div2" style="display: none">
              <div>
                the .pgm files may not work on machines prior to the MPC1000
              </div>
              <div>
                as you can read
                <a href="https://www.mpc-samples.com/article/mpc-file-compatibility-1" target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">here</a>, there are some different versions of the .pgm file format and the
                files on this site were generated using the
                MPC1000/2500 .pgm file format as a starting template. i didn't have access to the other .pgm formats
                when i created the files on this site.
              </div>
              <div>
                perhaps someone with an older version of the .pgm file format for MPC60 or 3000 can send some to
                me so I can try and generate the scales using this older format. find me on <a
                  href="https://github.com/EpleyWebServices/mpc-scales-pack" target="_blank">github</a> if you can help
                with this.
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>
