        <h3>scale programs (.pgm files)</h3>
        <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 10px">
          <li>
            <a class="toggle" id="showdiv8">
              - how do i install and load the files?
            </a>
            <div id="div8" style="display: none">
              after downloading the files from this site and extracting the files from the zipped folder, follow the
              instructions from your mpc manual for how to upload files
              to your mpc's internal hard drive or a compact flash card. once you
              have the scales pack on your mpc, you simply load the .pgm
              scale file into the project and change the current track's program
              to the desired scale and begin playing the pads. no matter which pad
              you hit, you will always be in scale... no accidentals here!
            </div>
          </li>

          <li>
            <a class="toggle" id="showdiv7">
              - what are the scales and how do i use them?
            </a>
            <div id="div7" style="display: none">
              <div>
                the scales are simply .pgm files with mapped midi note
                assignments, ordered into musical scales.
              </div>
              <div>
                they are intended to be used with an external midi sound module
                connected to your mpc.
              </div>
              <div>
                to use the programs, you just load and select the desired scale
                file on the current track of the main sequencer. now, when you hit
                the pads, the midi notes that are triggered will be in the desired
                scale.
              </div>
              <div>
                the scales can help discover and create chord progressions, sketch
                out melodies, or add basslines in the scale of your samples. it's
                also fun to improvise solos by hitting random pads to show off
                your advanced knowledge of music theory ;)
              </div>
              <div>
                follow the instructions from your mpc manual to connect your mpc
                to an external midi device. then, download the scales from this
                site and load 'em up to begin experimenting!
              </div>
              <div>
                to see the scales in action, go to the
                <a href="/scales/ENJOY!">scales player</a> to try them out in
                real-time.
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>

          <li>
            <a class="toggle" id="showdiv1">
              - how are the scales organized?
            </a>
            <div id="div1" style="display: none">
              <div>
                the root folder contains numbered folders ("-2", "-1", "0", "1",
                "2") which corresponds to the (midi) octave assigned to
                <code>PAD A01</code> (i.e. the starting point for the ascending
                scale).
              </div>
              <div>
                the second-level folders are the different scale categories:
                "All", "Chromatic", "Diminished", "Major", "Minor", and "Other".
                both "Major" and "Minor" folders contain pentatonic and
                non-pentatonic versions of each scale. in addition to the scales
                for each rootnote, the "Major" folder also contains a
                sub-directory for each rootnote for the various
                <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode_(music)">modes</a>
                of the scale. the "Other" folder contains over 100 various scales
                from around the world.
              </div>
              <div>
                the "All" folder (only included in the FULL version)
                contains every unique 5 to 9 note scale pattern (including all
                modes of each scale) within the 12-tone equally-tempered system of
                music, including named scales (where applicable) which also are
                listed in the "Other" folder for easier access. the "All" folder
                is not shown on the
                <a href="/scales/ENJOY!">scales player</a> page, because there
                were too many files. : (
              </div>
              <div>
                essentially, what you see on the
                <a href="/scales/ENJOY!">scales player</a> page is the "0" folder
                of the LITE version of the scales pack which doesn't include the
                "All" scales folder.
              </div>
              <div>
                please go to the <a href="/scales/ENJOY!">scales player</a> and
                see the directory on the left side of the page to better
                understand how the scales are organized.
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>

          <li>
            <a class="toggle" id="showdiv11">
              - how are the scales named? what do the numbers mean in the filename?
            </a>
            <div id="div11" style="display: none">
              <div>lets use an example scale file: <b>-2G#5311Iwato.pgm</b></div>
              <table style="margin-left: 25px; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px">
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <th>-2</th>
                    <td>
                      Starting octave, assigned to PAD A01 (i.e. the first note of
                      the ascending scale)
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <th>G#</th>
                    <td>Rootnote</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <th>5</th>
                    <td>This is a 5 note scale. (always a single digit 5-9)</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <th>31</th>
                    <td>
                      It is number 31 out of 66 unique 5 note scale patterns. (can
                      be one or two digits)
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <th>1</th>
                    <td>
                      It is the 1st mode of the scale pattern. (always a single
                      digit)
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <th>Iwato</th>
                    <td>
                      The name of the scale is Iwato. (there are more than one
                      name for many of the scales)
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>

              <div>
                scales in the "Chromatic", "Diminished", "Major", "Minor", and "Other" folders do not include the full
                scale numbers in their name, for the sake of simplicity.
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>

          <li>
            <a class="toggle" id="showdiv9">
              - can the scales be used with samples or keygroups?
            </a>
            <div id="div9" style="display: none">
              <div>
                unfortunately, no. the scales are only able to trigger midi notes
                in scale; not sample pitch or keygroups... :(
              </div>
              <div>
                if someone has an idea of how to potentially do this, i'd love to
                know about it.
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a class="toggle" id="showdiv12">
              - why is there a _.WAV file in every scale folder?
            </a>
            <div id="div12" style="display: none">
              <div>
                each pad in a .pgm file needs a sample assigned. if the assigned
                sample isn't loaded at the same time as the .pgm file, it will
                cause issues...
              </div>
              <div>
                the _.WAV file is an empty sample that is as small as possible and
                doesn't make a sound.
              </div>
              <div>don't delete the file—it's necessary!</div>
              <div>always save the _.WAV file with your project!</div>
              <div>
                and make sure you don't name any of your
                project's samples "_.WAV" since the sample would trigger whenever a scale
                pad plays.
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>

